  "prompt": "What does it mean when your left eye twitches?",
  "response": "Eye twitching, also known as eyelid twitching or myokymia, is usually a benign and temporary condition where your eyelid muscles contract involuntarily. It can affect either the left or right eye and may be caused by a variety of factors, including:\n\n1. **Fatigue**: Lack of sleep or excessive tiredness can lead to eye twitching.\n2. **Stress**: High levels of stress and anxiety are common triggers.\n3. **Caffeine and Alcohol**: Excessive consumption of caffeine or alcohol can contribute to twitching.\n4. **Eye Strain**: Prolonged screen time or focusing on a task for too long can strain the eyes, leading to twitching.\n5. **Dry Eyes**: Insufficient moisture in the eyes can cause irritation and twitching.\n6. **Nutritional Imbalances**: Deficiencies in certain nutrients, such as magnesium, can cause muscle spasms.\n\nMost cases of eye twitching are harmless and resolve on their own. However, persistent twitching that lasts for weeks or affects other parts of the face may require medical attention, as it could indicate a neurological condition or other underlying issues. If you're concerned, it's always a good idea to consult a healthcare professional.",
